{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"762a2db3-3600-4639-9dab-055ccba5e8c3","content":"With `MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0`, the switch is straightforward:\n\n1. **Remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>` property in your project file:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Before -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n\n<!-- After -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n</Project>\n```\n\n`MSTest.Sdk` defaults to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, so simply removing `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` is enough.\n\n2. **Run tests** with:\n   ```\n   dotnet test\n   ```\n   or directly via the built executable:\n   ```\n   dotnet run --project YourTest.csproj -- --list-tests\n   ```\n\n**Key behavioral differences to be aware of:**\n\n- **CLI options change** — e.g. `--filter` becomes `--filter` still works via `dotnet test`, but the native runner uses `--treenode-filter`.\n- **`.runsettings`** — still supported, passed via `--settings`.\n- **No more `.trx` by default** — add `<OutputType>trx</OutputType>` or pass `--report-trx` if you need TRX output.\n- **Parallel execution** — now controlled by the platform; review any `[Parallelize]` attributes.\n\nThat's it — no extra NuGet packages are needed since the SDK handles everything.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"647e8ce5-2e45-4af5-af50-c28752da2f65","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform in their MSTest project. This is a knowledge-based question about .NET testing configuration, so I can answer directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":451},"id":"98972497-5490-4c5a-b67d-adcfd95f7cf3","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:44:45.111Z","parentId":"5c702097-4004-4587-85e7-b3be9e75cc79"}
